    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-07-25T11:52:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-07-25T11:52:00-05:00" n="337"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d337">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EGDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> papers, “Telephone Conversations”</note>
                <head>No. 337<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by the Secretary of
                        State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1953-07-25T12:52:00-04:00"
                            >July 25, 1953—12:52 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Conversation With <persName>Frank Wisner</persName>
                    </hi>
                </p>
                <p>Mr. <persName>Wisner</persName> called with reference to the factual sheet that
                    had been sent over on Iran<note n="1" xml:id="d337fn1">See <ref
                            target="#d335fn2">footnote 2, Document 335</ref>.</note> (AWD at
                    Quantico) and wanted to know whether we needed anything by way of clarification?
                    The Secretary said he had not been too sure why it was sent him, and Mr.
                        <persName>Wisner</persName> said he understood it was the result of
                    telephone conversation between the two <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName>’ yesterday.<note n="2" xml:id="d337fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d335">Document 335</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>He stressed that the statement is actually factual and would have quite an
                    impact. The Secretary asked whether it was their idea that State or <gloss
                        target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> put it out, and <persName>Wisner</persName>
                    said whatever the Secretary wished. He planned to call <persName>Arthur
                        Krock</persName>, but knew that he was also a friend of the Secretary’s and
                    thought he might like to do so.</p>
                <p>The Secretary will look over the statement again and let Mr.
                        <persName>Wisner</persName> know (<persName>Wisner</persName> is going to
                    his farm at 2 p.m. but whoever is at his extension will be prepared to take it
                    from there, he will have talked to Krock in the meantime).</p>
                <p>He felt that if we got it out today it could be in the Monday morning
                        papers.<note n="3" xml:id="d337fn3">For a published version of this paper,
                        see <hi rend="italic">Newsweek</hi>, Aug. 10, 1953, p. 36.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
